ns of Senegal—Fischer explores the role of social living in the rise of primate intelligence and communication, ultimately asking what the ways in which other primates communicate can teach us about the evolution of human language. Funny and fascinating, Fischer’s tale roams from a dinner in the field shared with lionesses to insights gleaned from Rico, a border collie with an astonishing vocabulary, but its message is clear: it is humans who are the evolutionary mimics. The primate heritage visible in our species is far more striking than the reverse, and it is the monkeys who deserve to be seen. “The social life of macaques and baboons is a magnificent opera,” Fischer writes. “Permit me now to raise the curtain on it.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCognition in animals. 0aLearning in animals. 0aPrimatesxBehavior. 0aSocial behavior in animals. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aprimates, animals, animal kingdom, mental, brain, primatology, anthropology, scholarly, scholar, academic, school, educational, classroom, college, university, memoir, science, scientific, interdisciplinary, communication, africa, international, species, cognition, social studies, behavior, evolution, evolutionary, language, interpersonal, macaques, genes, vocalization, conflict, metacognition, sentience, baboon, fieldwork, research, hypothesis.1 aHenry Jr., Frederick B.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226124384423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226124384/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles